<paragraph id="8B8D36A1B464FFFAFF1A5EC5E7F7FF53" blockId="5.[136,1452,158,797]" box="[189,745,158,185]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">
<emphasis id="B946EAB3B464FFFAFF1A5EC5E427FF52" bold="true" box="[189,313,158,184]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Phenology</emphasis>
:—Flowering in May; fruiting in June.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8D36A1B464FFFAFF1A5E99E7EBFE87" blockId="5.[136,1452,158,797]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">
<emphasis id="B946EAB3B464FFFAFF1A5E99E481FF36" bold="true" box="[189,415,194,220]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Pollen morphology</emphasis>
:—Pollen grains of 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D22B464FFFAFDDE5E99E657FF36" authorityName="L. Xu &amp; T. G. Kang" authorityYear="2022" box="[633,841,194,220]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ranunculaceae" genus="Pulsatilla" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="200" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="saxatilis">
<emphasis id="B946EAB3B464FFFAFDDE5E99E657FF36" box="[633,841,194,220]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Pulsatilla saxatilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are spheroidal and pantoporate, having 9–12 apertures (
<figureCitation id="13092A24B464FFFAFF375EBDE410FEEB" box="[144,270,230,257]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,823,1501]" captionTargetId="figure-265@5.[340,1247,821,1501]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 5. Pollen grains (scanning electron microscopy) in Pulsatilla saxatilis (A, B; voucher: Fengcheng, Liaoning, north-east China, L. Xu et al. 210682150526013LY (LNCM)) and P. chinensis (C, D; voucher: L. Xu et al. 210213150423014LY (LNCM), Dalian, Liaoning, north-east China)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6358207" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6358207/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Fig. 5A, B</figureCitation>
). The pollen surface is rough and spinulate, and the spinules are unevenly distributed. The bases of the spinules are cushion-like, and the tops are acuminate. The spinules in the apertures are larger than those on the surface. In its putative closest ally, 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D22B464FFFAFE115F74E724FEA2" authorityName="Regel" authorityYear="1861" baseAuthorityName="Bunge" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[438,570,302,328]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ranunculaceae" genus="Pulsatilla" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="200" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chinensis">
<emphasis id="B946EAB3B464FFFAFE115F74E724FEA2" box="[438,570,302,328]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">P. chinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, pollen grains are tricolpate (
<figureCitation id="13092A24B464FFFAFC205F75E11DFEA3" box="[903,1027,302,329]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="5.[136,229,1526,1548]" captionTargetBox="[341,1247,823,1501]" captionTargetId="figure-265@5.[340,1247,821,1501]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 5. Pollen grains (scanning electron microscopy) in Pulsatilla saxatilis (A, B; voucher: Fengcheng, Liaoning, north-east China, L. Xu et al. 210682150526013LY (LNCM)) and P. chinensis (C, D; voucher: L. Xu et al. 210213150423014LY (LNCM), Dalian, Liaoning, north-east China)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6358207" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6358207/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Fig. 5C, D</figureCitation>
). Pollen morphology, therefore, lends strong support for the description of 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D22B464FFFAFD845F08E785FE86" authorityName="L. Xu &amp; T. G. Kang" authorityYear="2022" box="[547,667,338,364]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ranunculaceae" genus="Pulsatilla" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="200" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="saxatilis">
<emphasis id="B946EAB3B464FFFAFD845F08E785FE86" box="[547,667,338,364]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">P. saxatilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as new.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C328652AB464FFFAFF1A5F2DE5BBFE33" pageId="5" pageNumber="200" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8D36A1B464FFFAFF1A5F2DE5BBFE33" blockId="5.[136,1452,158,797]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">
<emphasis id="B946EAB3B464FFFAFF1A5F2DE4F3FE7A" bold="true" box="[189,493,374,400]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Distribution and habitat</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D22B464FFFAFDB75F2DE7F9FE7A" authorityName="L. Xu &amp; T. G. Kang" authorityYear="2022" box="[528,743,374,400]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ranunculaceae" genus="Pulsatilla" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="200" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="saxatilis">
<emphasis id="B946EAB3B464FFFAFDB75F2DE7F9FE7A" box="[528,743,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Pulsatilla saxatilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently known only from its 
<typeStatus id="54898803B464FFFAFB2F5F2CE1A6FE7B" box="[1160,1208,375,401]" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">type</typeStatus>
locality, i.e. Baiyun Mountain in Fengcheng, 
<collectingRegion id="49F6F843B464FFFAFE385FC1E771FE5E" box="[415,623,410,436]" country="China" name="Liaoning" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Liaoning province</collectingRegion>
, north-east 
<collectingCountry id="F3257631B464FFFAFD485FC1E62CFE5E" box="[751,818,410,436]" name="China" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">China</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="13092A24B464FFFAFCE65FC1E69AFE5F" box="[833,900,410,437]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[136,229,1241,1263]" captionTargetBox="[180,1415,214,1196]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[164,1423,190,1217]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Distribution of Pulsatilla saxatilis (▲)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6358209" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6358209/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="200">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). It grows on rocky cliffs at an altitude of ca. 
<quantity id="4CCA9B44B464FFFAFAD55FC1E5BFFE33" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="200" unit="m" value="1100.0">1100 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
